- One of the most important thing virtually *every* programmer must learn and remember is *if you have to scroll in order to read an entire function or method, it&#39;s too long!* :) 
- By spending some time organizing your code and abstracting it out into organized classes and methods, it makes it easier for you *and others* to understand what&#39;s going on and find bugs (ordering methods in the same logical progression as they are expected to be called is also helpful)
- The program you&#39;re writing would benefit from the use of case statements (https://www.rubyguides.com/2015/10/ruby-case/), which are also called &quot;switch statements&quot; in some other languages

The indentation in the code you provided is very inconsistently formatted so it&#39;s a bit hard to understand what a lot of things there do without a ton of effort, but my guess is that your issue here is once you verify there is a customer via `else if new_customer &amp;&amp; new_cus_pass`, you proceed to call `show_main_menu(new_customer)`. If you look at your `show_main_menu` method definition, you are printing the different options to the console but you never call `gets.chomp` to read in the selection. So that should be where you&#39;re getting stuck.

As an aside, querying for `Customer.find_by(username: user_name)` AND `Customer.find_by(password: pass_word)` doesn&#39;t make a lot of sense to do because:

 - A username has an expectation of being unique, but a password doesn&#39;t; more than one user may decide to use the same password
 - Because more than one person may choose the same password, `new_cus_pass` will return the first customer that has that password -- not necessarily the *right* customer
 - It&#39;s very inefficient to perform unnecessary database calls, so you always want to get what you need the first time around whenever possible. You can also query for multiple attributes in the same query, e.g., `Customer.find_by(username: user_name, password: pass_word)`; if the record isn&#39;t found, `find_by` will fail gracefully and return `nil`.

